# Browser Testing - MANDATORY When Developing Frontend Features

**CRITICAL**: Any frontend feature must be tested in the browser using the `cursor-ide-browser` MCP before being considered done.

## Golden Rule

```
🌐 TEST IN BROWSER — not just TypeScript
📸 TAKE SCREENSHOTS to verify UI
🔍 CHECK NETWORK REQUESTS for API errors
🐛 CATCH BUGS before the user does
```

---

## When to Test in the Browser

Test in the browser after **every** frontend change that affects:

- New pages or routes
- New components or UI elements
- Data fetching (API calls)
- Form interactions
- Navigation links
- Filters, dropdowns, selects
- Conditional rendering

---

## Browser Testing Workflow

### Step 1: Identify the correct deployment URL

The frontend is deployed on **Vercel**:
```
https://rent-management-app-frontend.vercel.app
```

Local dev server (if running):
```
http://localhost:3001
```

> ⚠️ The old Cloud Run URL (`rent-application-frontend-*.run.app`) is **NOT active** — do not use it.

### Step 2: Wait for Vercel deployment (after push)

After `git push origin main`, Vercel deploys automatically.
- Check that the new page/route is accessible before testing
- If the route returns 404, the deployment is still in progress — wait ~1 min

### Step 3: Navigate and snapshot

```
browser_navigate(url)
browser_snapshot()        ← always take snapshot first before clicking
```

### Step 4: Check network requests for API errors

```
browser_network_requests()  ← look for 401, 403, 500 errors
browser_console_messages()  ← look for JS errors
```

### Step 5: Interact with the UI

```
browser_click(ref)         ← use refs from snapshot
browser_take_screenshot()  ← verify visual output
```

### Step 6: Verify the feature works end-to-end

- Does the data load?
- Are dropdowns populated?
- Do filters work?
- Are error states shown when APIs fail?

---

## Common Bugs to Catch

| Symptom | Likely Cause | How to Detect |
|--------|-------------|--------------|
| Empty dropdown | API returns 401/400 | `browser_network_requests()` |
| Page shows 404 | Route not deployed yet | Wait and retry |
| No data in table | API filter too restrictive | Check network URL params |
| Redirect to login | Token expired or missing | Check 401 response |
| Component crashes | TypeScript/runtime error | `browser_console_messages()` |

---

## Lessons Learned (from real bugs)

### Bug: Payments page dropdown was empty

- **Root cause**: Query used `status=ACTIVE` filter that returned 401 because
  the token was invalid **or** no leases matched the filter.
- **Detected by**: `browser_network_requests()` showed the API call returned 401.
- **Fixed by**: Removing the restrictive filter, loading all leases instead.

### Lesson: Always check network requests after building any data-fetching component.

---

## MCP Browser Tools Quick Reference

```
browser_navigate(url)           — navigate to URL
browser_snapshot()              — get page structure and element refs
browser_take_screenshot()       — capture visual screenshot
browser_click(ref)              — click element
browser_fill(ref, value)        — fill input field
browser_select_option(ref, val) — select dropdown option
browser_network_requests()      — show recent network calls + status codes
browser_console_messages()      — show browser console errors/warnings
browser_lock()                  — lock before interactions
browser_unlock()                — unlock when done
```

---

## Checklist Before Marking a Feature as Done

- [ ] TypeScript compiles: `npx tsc --noEmit`
- [ ] Deployed to Vercel (after push)
- [ ] Page/route loads in browser (no 404)
- [ ] No API errors in network requests (no 401/500)
- [ ] No JS errors in browser console
- [ ] Data populates correctly (dropdowns, tables, cards)
- [ ] Interactions work (click, select, submit)
- [ ] Screenshot taken to confirm visual output

---

**Rationale:** TypeScript checks only validate types at compile-time. Runtime bugs
(wrong API calls, auth failures, empty states, rendering issues) are only caught
by actually running the app in the browser. A 5-minute browser test saves hours
of debugging production issues.
